Adjectives (expanded / expressive)

mogrificent        adjective; bringing about mogri in a way that feels ample, fitting, or quietly impressive
mogrific           adjective; having the effect or character of mogrification
mogrificatory      adjective; serving or intended to serve a mogrifying function
mogrificationistic adjective; pertaining to mogrification in an overextended, theoretical, or scholastic sense
mogrificationisticant adjective; deliberately baroque or clown-academic form indicating excessive or self-aware mogrification discourse

Adjectives (evaluative / interpretive)

mogritiv        adjective; tending to increase, support, or sustain mogri; experienced as beneficial or life-giving with respect to mogri

Adjectives (directional / causal)

mogritant        adjective; actively provoking, stimulating, or drawing out mogri; tending to make mogri arise or intensify

Nouns (informal / emergent)

mogrif            noun; an informal or emergent instance, trace, or residue of mogrification; a small, often unplanned manifestation of mogri noticed after the fact


Abstract nouns (qualities / states)

mogrificence       noun; the quality or state of being mogrificent
mogrificity        noun; the degree or intensity of mogri present in a thing or situation


Adverbs

mogrifically       adverb; in a mogrific or mogrificent manner; by way of mogrification



Medical / Academic / Scientific Fantasy (explicitly non-clinical)

DISCLAIMER:
The following terms deliberately resemble medical or scientific language.
They are fictional, allegorical, and non-diagnostic.
They must not be interpreted as real medical, biological, or clinical entities.

mogremia        noun; a fictional or allegorical condition denoting an undefined mogri-related presence “in the blood”; used only in narrative, metaphorical, or speculative contexts

demogremia      noun; fictional reversal or absence of mogremia; narrative placeholder for “nothing measurable, but something missing”

mogrimic        adjective; having the appearance or rhetoric of scientific legitimacy without making empirical claims

mogrimetric     adjective; describing an imagined or symbolic measurement of mogri, not a real assay or metric


